title: For Sale/Trade:   From CMP.....1955 Springfield Armory Garand with Sling, 5 En Bloc Clips, & Hard Carry Case
postcontent: This is a service grade 1955 Springfield (SA) Armory M1 Garand; the rifle that General George S. Patton referred to as: " the greatest battlefield implement ever devised." She was purchased through the Civilian Marksmanship Program. The rifle is chambered in the venerable 30-06 cartridge. The SA barrel dates to 4-55. The SA rifle serial number dates to 1955 as well. That, along with like condition and Patina, suggests the barrel is original to the gun. The serial number will be given upon phone conversation only. There are no visible import marks. The stainless gas seal is the only area exhibiting any significant wear. Rust is non-existent, nor are there any signs of major battle scars. Normal wear is minimal for the time frame. There is evidence of a faint ordnance cartouche stamp on the stock just below the left side of receiver.  The barrel is shiny and remains accurate. The rifle functions wonderfully and is accompanied by 5 en bloc clips.  The rifle wears an OD nylon sling, befitting of the time period in both use and appearance. The weapon has the normal matching of the major US manufacturers parts of that time:Receiver- SABarrel- SA 4-1955Trigger Group- International Harvester Op Rod- SA Bolt- Harrington and RichardsonSights (SA). The sights are in excellent mechanical condition and show minimal wear. They remain audible, tactile and precise on the firing line.This Garand is an excellent example of American Ingenuity. It retains the history of " the greatest generation", and will continue to be a legacy for generations to admire.*Numerous additional photos upon request.  Comes with hard case.

title: For Sale:  38 REVOLVER & TIN AMMO BOX FOUND IN CAR OWNED BY BUCK BARROW (Bonnie & Clyde's brother) looks complete...rare estate find.  US REVOLVER CO.
postcontent: This listing is for a small revolver metal ammunition box from a Pittsburgh estate.  A neighbor of ours passed away last year, and his older brother had been a Missouri State Policeman back in the 1920's.  The older brother had been involved in the search for the bank robbing Barrow Gang.  There had been a shootout where the Barrow Gang escaped, and had abandoned one of their cars...an early Ford sedan.  The older brother had been one of the first on the scene, and had found these items in a satchel on the back seat floor.  He put them in his car to keep as a souvenir, as the Barrow's were widely known notorious criminals.  After a few days passed, he began to realize that he could loose his job, pension & freedom from the keeping of this gun - and he squirreled it away.  He only showed to a few people.  The lawman and his brother are deceased now...so it is time for the items to be passed along.  The gun is marked US REVOLVER CO., and had a serial number of 9022 stamped under the trigger guard.  It looks complete & rotates the cylinder when squeezed double action style.  The hammer stays back when you cock it.  I have not tried to fire it....to me it is a museam piece.  Also included is the metal ammunition box.  You can just make out the words "Revolver Cartridges".  Email any questions & I can send you additional photos.  Thank you for stopping in.

postcontent: BRAND NEW KAHR CM9 NEVER BEEN FIRED COMES WITH TWO MAGS. BUYER MUST BE WILLING TO DO A BILL OF SALE  AND PROVIDE A COPY OF DRIVER LIC AND CCP. KACM9093 PRODUCT DETAILS FAMILY:CM9 Series MODEL:CM9 TYPE:Semi-Auto PistolACTION:Double Action Only FINISH:Matte Stainless STOCK/FRAME:Polymer Frame STOCK/GRIPS:Black PolymerWEIGHT:15.9 oz.CALIBER/GAUGE:9mm CAPACITY:6+1 # OF MAGS:1 MAGAZINE DESC:6 rd.BARREL:3" OVERALL LENGTH:5.42"SIGHTS:FixedThe CM Series takes the value priced features from Kahr's CW series (3.6" barrel 9mm, .40 S&W and .45 ACP models) and incorporates these features into a smaller 3" barrel package. The CM9093 has the same external dimensions as the PM9093 which make it ideal for concealed carry by licensed civilians and law enforcement personnel. The CM9093 is chambered in a 9 x 19 caliber, has a 3.0" barrel and an overall length of 5.42, with a height of 4.0". The pistol weighs in at 14 ounces plus 1.9 ounces for the 6 rd stainless steel magazine. Differences between the CM models and PM models are the CM9093 has a conventional rifled barrel instead of the match grade polygonal barrel on Kahr's PM series; the CM slide stop lever is MIM (metal-injection-molded) instead of machined; the CM series slide has fewer machining operations and uses simple roll marking instead of engraved markings and finally the CM series are shipped with one magazine instead of two magazines.Kahr's seven patents are incorporated into the CM9093 resulting in benefits not available in other compact semi-autos on the market today. The black polymer frame features patented 4140 steel inserts molded into the frame in the front and back for added rigidity and strength which can withstand firing thousands of rounds. Kahr's incomparable cocking cam trigger system employs a patented cam to both unlock the firing pin block (passive safety) and complete cocking and releasing of the firing pin. The system provides a "safe-cam action" and unbelievably smooth double action only trigger stroke, fast to fire in critical defensive situations.Kahr's two patents covering the offset recoil lug and the trigger bar attachment allow Kahr's barrel to fit lower in the frame and since there is no hammer the shooter's hand is further up the grip resulting in less felt recoil and quick follow-up shots. The CM9 boasts real sights which are drift adjustable in the rear and a pinned-in polymer front sight featuring a white bar-dot configuration. Finally the slide locks back after firing the last round - another feature missing on a number of lower cost compact semi-auto pistols.The CM9 slide is only .90 inch wide and machined from solid 416 stainless slide with a matte finish, each gun is shipped with one 6 rd stainless steel magazine with a flush baseplate. Magazines are USA made, plasma welded, tumbled to remove burrs and feature Wolff Gunsprings. The magazine catch in the polymer frame is all metal and will not wear out on the stainless steel magazine after extended use.Kahr offers the CM series at a great value price but did not compromise on the features, accuracy or reliability found in all Kahr pistols.
